03998nam a22005295i 9780773592162DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735921627 a10.1515/97807735921622doi  a(DE-B1597)655021  a(OCoLC)875729252  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPH666.21.A6bZ85 2014 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a894/.545122231 aSalumets, Thomas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnforced Flourishing :bUnderstanding Jaan Kaplinski /cThomas Salumets. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tFrom Tartu to the Calgary Olympics -- tTroubled Sage -- tDon't Touch that Rock, Sisyphus -- tThe Medium Is Not the Message -- tBody Signals -- tDesire for Dependence -- tBeyond Dissidence -- tSelf-colonization -- tThe Art of Unforced Flourishing -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAre we ill-suited for this world? Among Europe's major contemporary poets, Estonia's Jaan Kaplinski offers a rare vision of human advancement and fulfillment: the less we intervene the more we flourish. But how then can we remain involved in what evolves of its own accord? How can we move away from a life forged by human design towards a quietly attentive yet spontaneous responsiveness? In Unforced Flourishing, Thomas Salumets seeks access to Kaplinski's life and work and finds a path to the signature of his thinking. He uncovers a man who craves human closeness that few, if any, can provide, a writer drawn towards wordless communication in a world of words, signs, and symbols, who yearns for the sacred in secular times, and who detects more richness in nature than in the human imagination. Salumets describes Kaplinski as an intellectual attracted to a contrarian sense of self, art, and culture, who searches for his homeland's mystical connections at a time when Estonia firmly aligns with values and modes of thought vastly different from his own. What emerges is a mentality firmly rooted in the belief that the greatest risk to human fulfillment results from human beings themselves. The first major study in English of one of Eastern Europe's most important literary figures, Unforced Flourishing details Kaplinski’s embrace of that which is undifferentiated, intuitive, non-calculative, and natural in the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPoets, EstonianxBiographyx20th century. 0aPoets, Estoniany20th centuryvBiography. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359216240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773592162423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773592162/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles